'''Narukami Shrine'' (Narujinja) is located in {{ill|lt=Wakayama Prefecture|Q131314|WD=Q131314|1=Wakayama Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Wakayama City|Q200747|WD=Q200747|1=Wakayama (city)}}{{ill|lt=Narukami (Wakayama City)|Q17209155|WD=Q17209155|lt=Narukami|1=Narukami}}. {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} ({{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}) and {{ill|lt=Modern shrine rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Old shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|lt=Murasha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined God ===
The following three deities are currently enshrined. </ref>.
* '''{{ill|lt=Hayaakitsuhiko Hayaakitsuhime|Q11326733|WD=Q11326733|lt=Hayaakitsuhiko no Mikoto|1=Hayakitsuhiko and Hayakitsuhime}}''' (Hayaakitsuhiko Mikoto) - Left shrine (facing the right shrine).
* '''{{ill|lt=Hayaakitsuhiko Hayaakitsuhime|Q11326733|WD=Q11326733|lt=Hayaakitsuhime no Mikoto|1=Hayakitsuhiko and Hayakitsuhime}}''' (Hayaakitsuhime Mikoto) - Left shrine (facing the right shrine).
* '''{{ill|lt=Futodama|Q11059539|WD=Q11059539|lt=Tentadama no Mikoto|1=Futodama}}''' (Amenofutodama no Mikoto) - Right shrine (facing left shrine). {{ill|lt=Ibe-san|Q8189229|WD=Q8189229|1=Inbe clan}}Ancestor God.

The two deities enshrined are the gods of Mito (the gods of the port). As far back as the {{ill|lt=Enkyo|Q1183728|WD=Q1183728|1=Enkyō (Edo period)}} 3rd year ({{ill|lt=1746|Q7589|WD=Q7589|1=1746}}), in the "Nanki Shrine Record", it appears that the two deities, Hayaakitsuhiko and Hayaakitsuhime, are enshrined {{Sfn|Naru Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}. However, the earlier "Nanki Meishoshi" states that it is unknown, and it is thought that the enshrined deity was unknown in the early {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}{{Sfn|Narujinja (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}.Later, in ``{{ill|lt=Kii Zoku Fudoki|Q11604964|WD=Q11604964|1=Kii Zoku Fudoki}},'' he questioned the theory that two gods were enshrined, Hayaakitsuhiko and Hayaakitsuhime, since there was only one deity enshrined at Narukin Shrine in the ``Engishiki,'' and advocated the theory that Tentadama-no-Mikoto was the enshrined deity.{{Sfn|Narujinsha (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}. This speculation is based on the theory that the area around this area is compared to the area of ``Ibe-go'' that appears in ``{{ill|lt=Japanese name Ruijusho|Q2702542|WD=Q2702542|1=Wamyō Ruijushō}}'', and in the same text, it is said that a person lived in this area. {jalink|Ibe clan|Q8189229}} (Kiibe clan) is said to have enshrined its ancestral deity, Tenta Tama no Mikoto {{Sfn|Naru Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}. In addition, the same article states that when Naru Shrine, which had been in ruins, was rebuilt in 4 ({{ill|lt=1719|Q6902|WD=Q6902|1=1719}}), two deities were considered: Hayaakitsuhiko and Hayaakitsuhime. However, Kii-Ibe is not a family of Inebekushi whose ancestor is Tenta Tama-no-Mikoto, but a family of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kikokuzō|1=UNKNOWN}}, and {{ill|lt=Hikosa Chi-no-Mikoto|Q135327097|WD=Q135327097|1=Hikosachi no Mikoto}} is its ancestor deity, according to ``{{ill|lt=Kogo Shui|Q531555|WD=Q531555|1=Kogo Shūi}}.'' Also, the fourth book of ``Mochizuki'' and ``Sho Keiki,'' which is another name for the founder of Kikuni-zukuri, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Takuma Tama no Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}. </ref>'s father is said to be a Narukami ({{ill|lt=Raijin|Q12808082|WD=Q12808082|1=Raijin}}) called {{ill|lt=Raijin|Q12808082|WD=Q12808082|1=Raijin}}, and in the Otomo clan genealogy in "Furuya family family history" and "Kamibetsu genealogy," Tenrai no Mikoto is said to be ``Narukami Shrine (Koreya), Nagusa district, Kii province.''<ref name="keifu2">Keninobu Nakata "Shinbetsu Genealogy", {{ill|lt=Tokyo National Museum|Q653433|WD=Q653433|1=Tokyo National Museum}} Digital Library. </ref>.Based on the Tentaitama no Mikoto theory, in {{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|WD=Q234510|1=Heisei era}}8 ({{ill|lt=1996|Q2070|WD=Q2070|1=1996}}), {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Tentadama no Mikoto Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} ({{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Kashihara City|Q496319|WD=Q496319|1=Kashihara, Nara}}Ibe Town), the spirit of Tentadama no Mikoto was once again solicited and enshrined in the main shrine.<ref name="historical book"/>.

=== History ===

=== Founding ===
According to the shrine biography cited in "Ki Meisho Zue", around the time of {{ill|lt=Emperor Koan|Q312821|WD=Q312821|1=Emperor Kōan}} (sixth generation), the god {{ill|lt=Ha It is said that there was an oracle to enshrine Yaakitsuhiko Hayaakitsuhime|Q11326733|WD=Q11326733|lt=Hayaakitsuhiko-no-Mikoto|1=Hayakitsuhiko and Hayakitsuhime}}, and Naru-jinja Shrine was founded as a result of this enshrinement. The company name ``Naru'' is said to be a name related to a river, as it is assumed in ``{{ill|lt=Kii Zoku Fudoki|Q11604964|WD=Q11604964|1=Kii Zoku Fudoki}}'' that it means water flowing from a valley called ``Narumizu'' or ``Narutaki''. {{Sfn|Naru Shrine (Gods)|1986}}On the other hand, {{ill|lt=Shohei (Japan)|Q1324874|WD=Q1324874|lt=Shohei|1=Jōhei}} ({{ill|lt=931|Q24789|WD=Q24789|1=931}}-{{ill|lt=938|Q24794|WD=Q24794|1=938}}) link|Japanese Ruijusho|Q2702542}}", you can see the entry "Inbe" as {{ill|lt=go|Q130458414|WD=Q130458414|1=go}} of Nagusa District.<ref name="Ibego"/>. This is believed to be near Inbe, Wakayama City, south of Narukin Shrine, and the area is said to have been the {{ill|lt=honkan|Q846706|WD=Q846706|lt=honkanchi|1=Korean clans}} of {{ill|lt=Ibe clan|Q8189229|WD=Q8189229|1=Inbe clan}} (Kii Inbe) in Kii. Nagusa District, Ibe-go section, Kobe-go section. </ref>. Also, in the same book, ``Nabe'' appears next to ``Ibe'', but this is a misprint of ``Kobe'', and is thought to mean ``Ibe Kobe'', that is, the god of Inbe (a private house attached to a shrine).<ref name="Ibe-go"/> Relatedly, in the ``Shinshokakuchofusho'' {{ill|lt=Daido (Japan)|Q1373191|WD=Q1373191|lt=Daido|1=Daidō}} 1st year ({{ill|lt=806|Q30021|WD=Q30021|1=806}}), there are mentions of 10 of the 20 households of Inabe deity in Kobe <ref name="Ibego"/>. It is certain that Kobe was located at Naru-jinja Shrine from the description of ``50 bunches of sake rice, divine tax'' in the Shijiki-sai Ainosai article of the ``Engishiki'', so it is thought that these Inabe-Kobe were attached to Naru-jinja Shrine, and Naru-jinja Shrine was enshrined as the guardian deity of Kii Inabe.<ref name="Ibego"/> It is also assumed that these Kobes were distributed around Narukami, Wakayama City, where Narukami Shrine is located <ref name="Ibego"/>.In addition, in "{{ill|lt=Kogo shui|Q531555|WD=Q531555|1=Kogo Shūi}}", Kiibe is a descendant of {{ill|lt=Hikosato no Mikoto|Q135327097|WD=Q135327097|1=Hikosachi no Mikoto}}, and is the ruler of Nagusa District. It is written that he lived in Kigo and Arakago (neither of which have "Wamyosho") and was responsible for paying tribute of lumber and building palaces and shrines. </ref>.

=== Outline ===
In national history, {{ill|lt=Jōkan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} In the first year ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), there is an article about the promotion of {{ill|lt=Divine rank|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} from the 8th grade of Jugoi to the 8th grade of Jushii (Junior 4th rank and lower rank) in the first year ({{Sfn|Narujinsha (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}.In "{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, {{ill|lt=Kiokuni|Q864053|WD=Q864053|1=Kii Province}}{{ill|lt=Nagusa District|Q11415547|WD=Q11415547|1=Nagusa district}} has "Narujin Shrine Meishin University It will be listed at {{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}} as ``Monthly Ainame Shinnai'' and {{ill|lt=Monthly Festival|Q11516161|WD=Q11516161|1=Tsukinami-no-Matsuri}} and {{ill|lt=Ainamesai|Q11581944|WD=Q11581944|1=Ainame Festival}}・It is written that it was deposited in {{ill|lt=Heihaku|Q11481885|WD=Q11481885|1=Hanpei}} at {{ill|lt=Ninamesai|Q11501518|WD=Q11501518|1=Niiname-no-Matsuri}}{{Sfn|Narukinsha (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}. There are many famous shrines in Kii Province, but the ones that received dedications at the three festivals are Narukinja Shrine, {{ill|lt=Maezen Shrine, Kunikake Shrine|Q888184|WD=Q888184|lt=Maejin Shrine|1=Hinokuma Shrine}}, {{ja There were only four shrines: link|Mae-mae Jingu/Kokukake Shrine|Q888184|Kunikake Shrine}} and {{ill|lt=Itaukeso Shrine|Q11379271|WD=Q11379271|1=Itakiso shrine}}. Regarding these four companies, please refer to "{{ill|lt=Reishūka|Q11378321|WD=Q11378321|1=Ryōshūge}}" Jingirei<ref group="hara">"Reishūkai" Volume 7 (Jingirei) Nakafuyujo Kamiusaōsai. </ref>Also, there is a description that it was listed at Hoheisha Shrine on the occasion of the Aijo Festival on Kami U no Hi in November as ``Mae, Kokukensu, Itaukeso, Narukami'' {{Sfn|Narujinsha (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}.In the storage rice book of {{ill|lt=Eiroku|Q1143341|WD=Q1143341|1=Eiroku}}3 ({{ill|lt=1048|Q19359|WD=Q19359|1=1048}}), 340 steps of Narukami Shrine rice fields can be seen {{Sfn|Narukin Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}. Also, in ``{{ill|lt=Kinokuni Jinmyocho|Q17210008|WD=Q17210008|1=Kii no Kuni Jinmyō-chō}}'', it is written as ``Shoichii Naru-Okami'' {{Sfn|Naru Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}.

{{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} In 13 ({{ill|lt=1585|Q6736|WD=Q6736|1=1585}}), {{ill|lt=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|Q187550|WD=Q187550|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi}}'s {{ill|lt=Kishū Conquest|Q10855721|WD=Q10855721|1=Battle of Kishuu}} {{ill|lt=Ota Castle (Ki Province)|Q10941625|WD=Q10941625|lt=Ota Castle|1=Ōta Castle}}It is said that during the water attack, the surrounding area, including Narukin Shrine, was greatly devastated. The shrine building was constructed in {{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}}4 ({{ill|lt=1719|Q6902|WD=Q6902|1=1719}}), and five Kanda shrines were donated {{Sfn|Narujinja (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was ranked as {{ill|lt=murasha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} in the {{ill|lt=modern shrine rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}. In the 40th year of the Meiji era ({{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|WD=Q2048|1=1907}}), in accordance with the ordinance to enshrine shrines, the nearby Shikinai shrines Kenmaon Shrine and Katsuchi Shrine were enshrined within the shrine grounds.

