=== Kenmaon Shrine ===
``Katamaoto Shrine'' (Katamanoto Shrine) is a shrine within the precincts of Narukin Shrine. {{ill|lt=Modern company rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Old company rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|lt=murasha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. Currently, it is enshrined together with Kotsuchi Shrine.

The following deities are enshrined:
* Kamiadaka Ashitsuhime no Mikoto {{Sfn|Katsuchi Shrine/Kanmaon Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1987|p=58-59}}
*: Another name for {{ill|lt=Konohana Sakuyabime|Q1781862|WD=Q1781862|lt=Konohana Sakuyahime no Mikoto|1=Konohanasakuya-hime}}.

In national history, {{ill|lt=Jōkan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} In the first year ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}, he was conferred {{ill|lt=Divine Rank|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}}, which is the upper rank of Jugoi, and in the seventh year of Jogan ({{ill|lt=865 In 1983|Q30350|WD=Q30350|1=865}}), it was ranked as a government shrine, and in the 8th year of Jogan ({{ill|lt=866|Q23872|WD=Q23872|1=866}}), there is a record that it was conferred the rank of Junior Fourth Rank and Lower.{{Sfn|Kanshin Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}."{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} is {{ill|lt=Kiokuni|Q864053|WD=Q864053|1=Kii Province}}{{jalink |Nagusa District|Q11415547}} is described as "Kanmaon Shrine" and is listed as {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikiuchi|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikinaisha}}, and in "{{ill|lt=Kinokuni Jinmyocho|Q17210008|WD=Q17210008|1=Kii no Kuni Jinmyō-chō}}" it is listed as "Shoichii Shrine". ``Arimaon Okami'' is compared to Kenmaon Shrine {{Sfn|Kanmaon Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}. Relatedly, in "{{ill|lt=Japanese name Ruijusho|Q2702542|WD=Q2702542|1=Wamyō Ruijushō}}", "Arima" is mentioned as {{ill|lt=go|Q130458414|WD=Q130458414|1=go}} of Nagusa District, and it is determined that it is near Narukami, Wakayama City. </ref>.

Kenmaon Shrine was originally located approximately 300 meters northeast of Naru Shrine {{Sfn|Kanmaon Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}. At his place of birth, there is a monument erected as ``Katsune Shrine Kyoho Kotatsu'', which appears to be inscribed in the year {{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}}9 ({{ill|lt=1724|Q6926|WD=Q6926|1=1724}}) {{Sfn|Katsune Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}.{{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} April 7th ({{ill|lt=1874|Q7761|WD=Q7761|1=1874}}), {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Modern company rating system|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{Sfn|Katsuchi Shrine/Kanmaon Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1987|p=58-59}} listed as {{ill|lt=Murasha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. In 1907 ({{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|WD=Q2048|1=1907}}), it was relocated to the precincts of Narukin Shrine in accordance with the ordinance to enshrine shrines. Later, a branch spirit was summoned to the shrine in Wakayama City, and the shrine building was rebuilt (currently Kenma-on Shrine, {{Coord|34|12|50.79|N|135|12|9.45|E|region:JP-30_type:landmark|name=Kanma-on Shrine (descendant shrine)}}).

The shrine is as follows.
* Records of {{ill|lt=Divine Rank|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} dedication in the history of the Six Kingdoms (all written as "Kanma Ongami")
** {{ill|lt=Jōgan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} May 26th, 1st year ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), from upper 6th rank to upper junior fifth rank (``{{ill|lt=Japan Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}'')
** On May 17, 7th year of Jogan era ({{ill|lt=865 years|Q30350|WD=Q30350|1=865}}), he was listed as a government shrine (``Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku'')
** Leap March 13, 8th year of the Jogan era ({{ill|lt=866|Q23872|WD=Q23872|1=866}}), from the top of the fifth rank to the bottom of the fourth rank (``Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku'')
* After Six Kingdoms History
** Shoichii ("{{ill|lt=Kiokuni Shinto Namecho|Q17210008|WD=Q17210008|1=Kii no Kuni Jinmyō-chō}}") - Written as "Arimaon Okami".

=== Katsuchi Shrine ===
'''Katsuchi Shrine'' (Katsuchi Shrine) is a shrine within the precincts of Narukinja Shrine. {{ill|lt=Modern company rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Old company rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|lt=murasha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. Currently, it is enshrined together with Kenmaon Shrine.

The following deities are enshrined.
* {{ill|lt=Kagutsuchi|Q1640658|WD=Q1640658|lt=Encounter with Tsuchi no Mikoto|1=Kagu-tsuchi}} (Kagutsuchi no Mikoto) {{Sfn|Katsuchi Shrine/Kanmaon Shrine (Shikiuchi)|1987|p=58-59}}

[[File:Naru-jinja Sakamatsu-sha.JPG|thumb|200px|right|{{center|Sakamatsu Shrine (Narukami, Wakayama City)<br />The former enshrinement site of Katsuchi Shrine. }}]]
"{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} is {{ill|lt=Kiokuni|Q864053|WD=Q864053|1=Kii Province}}{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Nakusa District|1=UNKNOWN}}, it is written as ``Katsuchi Shrine'' and is listed as {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikiuchi|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikinaisha}}, but in some manuscripts it is annotated as ``Narukami Sue Shrine'' {{Sfn|Katsuchi Shrine Ruins (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}. Also, in ``{{ill|lt=Kiokuni Jinmyocho|Q17210008|WD=Q17210008|1=Kii no Kuni Jinmyō-chō}}'' it is written as ``Junior Fourth Rank Upper Katsuchijin'' {{Sfn|Katsuchi Shrine Ruins (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}.Kotsuchi Shrine was originally located about 200 meters northeast of Naruko Shrine. rd|34|13|44.05|N|135|12|52.10|E|region:JP-30_type:landmark|name=Gakamatsu Shrine (formerly Katsuchi Shrine)}}). {{Sfn|Katsuchi Shrine Ruins (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}} It is said that it was in ruins in the early {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}} due to the military fire of the {{ill|lt=Kishū Conquest|Q10855721|WD=Q10855721|1=Battle of Kishuu}}. At his place of birth, there is a monument erected as ``Katsuchijin Keian Kotora'', which appears to be inscribed in the year {{ill|lt=Keian|Q1146135|WD=Q1146135|1=Keian}}3 ({{ill|lt=1650|Q6951|WD=Q6951|1=1650}}) {{Sfn|Katsuchi Shrine Ruins (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}. {{ill|lt=Enkyo|Q1183728|WD=Q1183728|1=Enkyō (Edo period)}} 3rd year ({{ill|lt=1746|Q7589|WD=Q7589|1=1746}}) "Nanki Jinja Roku" describes Kotsuchi Shrine as "Muhoden erected stone monument" {{Sfn|Katsuchi Shrine Ruins (Heibonsha)|1983|p=370}}.

In April of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), he was ranked as {{ill|lt=murasha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} in the {{ill|lt=modern company ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}. In 1907 ({{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|WD=Q2048|1=1907}}), it was relocated to the precincts of Narukin Shrine in accordance with the ordinance to enshrine shrines.

The shrine is as follows.
* After Six Kingdoms History** Junior Fourth Rank Upper (``{{ill|lt=Kiokuni Shinto Name Book|Q17210008|WD=Q17210008|1=Kii no Kuni Jinmyō-chō}}'') - Written as ``Katsuchijin''.

